[Student "S"]
{With 20 HCP and balanced distribution you should open 2NT. Do not let the good 4-card \S suit sway you to anything else. Partner bids 3NT and everybody passes.

South plays 3NT. West leads the \HJ. You try the \HQ, but East plays the \HK.

Winner List: \S = 1 : \H = 0 : \D = 4 : \C = 1 :: Total = 6

You need 3 more winners and at least 2 of them must come from \Ss. Furthermore you don't want East to lead \Cs through your King. Your best hope is that East holds the \SK so you can finesse.  

So you win the \HA and start thinking about dummy entries. Your obvious entries are the \DK and \DJ. If East holds only two small \Ss with his \SK, then two entries will be enough. But what if East holds \S K x x x ? Can you find a third entry to dummy? 

If the \Ds split 3-2 the answer is <b>YES</b>. Play the \DA, then lead your \D8 to dummy's \DJ. Watch carefully to see if both defenders follow to this trick. They do. Play a \S to your \ST, which holds the trick. Play your \DQ to dummy's \DK. Finesse the \S again. Return to dummy by playing your \D5 to dummy's \D6, then finesse the \S one last time.

If the \Ds had split 4-1 you would not have been able to enter dummy three times. That would have been very unlucky.

If you played your \D5 too early you would not have been able to enter dummy three times even when there was a 3-2 split. That would have been very unsmart.}
[Play "W"]HJ

